text: Habesha is just ancient name of society which were under the rule of Aksumite kingdom which includes todays Tigrai region off ethiopia Eritrea northern part of the Amhara region eastern and north east Sudan That means it includes many tribes with their own different languages and cultures Some of them have common words tradition and intermarriage background until this day Unfortunately for a long several generations in the past until this day the name of Habesha has been used to describe for specific tribes who are mainly Orthodox Church Christian followers In other words it doesnt include islamic religion followers For example in Eritrea the Kunama tribe who are mainly none Muslims and none Christians the rest of Eritrean tribes dominantly muslims all Sudan people western and northeastern ethiopian people and Muslim population of ethiopia in general dont describe themselves as Habesha people In this case the name of Habesha doesnt properly indicate the people under its name The most likely is that the name Habesha was generally used by the ancient Arabs to describe black people of the the horn of Africa
original: Habesha is just ancient name of society which were under the rule of Aksumite kingdom which includes today's Tigrai region off ethiopia, Eritrea, northern part of the Amhara region, eastern and north east Sudan. That means, it includes many tribes with their own different languages and cultures. Some of them have common words, tradition, and intermarriage background until this day. Unfortunately, for a long several generations in the past until this day, the name of Habesha has been used to describe for specific tribes who are mainly Orthodox Church Christian followers. In other words, it doesn't include islamic religion followers. For example, in Eritrea, the Kunama tribe who are mainly none Muslims and none Christians, the rest of Eritrean tribes dominantly muslims, all Sudan people, western and northeastern ethiopian people and Muslim population of ethiopia in general don't describe themselves as Habesha people. In this case, the name of Habesha doesn't properly indicate the people under its name. The most likely is that the name Habesha was generally used by the ancient Arabs to describe black people of the the horn of Africa.

original:
What makes this song unique? 

1) Its catchy beginning with beautiful melody made of traditional instrument 

2) The video clip is the most meaning full ever. It starts with a lonely girl striving in a foreign  country, and suddenly  struck by a beauty of a handsome habesha;  and then takes us  through a typical Habesha dating all the  way from introducing, come together with friends and finally ended with her dream man. (the clip is so effective, some films need 90 minutes to convey the same message).

3) While the story going on Abby with her sweet voice shares how the girl is happy and shows us as if some one is dreaming on dancing at the beach of a beautiful sea because the dream is coming true.

4) As the catchy traditional melody develops itself to a full orchestra the lonely girl to slowly but surely  gets to know her dream man and comes to full of life with singing, dancing, jumping, smiling. 

5) And finally everything comes to a happy ending. 

Each music must have a story. This one is lucky the story is told perfectly.
